                    /===================================\
                    |       Keyboard layout             |
                    |           us_tj2                  |
                    |           US/German (TJ, v2)      |
                    \===================================/

how to INSTALL:
===============

Copy the file ``us_tj2'' to /usr/share/X11/xkb/symbols/
You can now load the layout with
   $ setxkbmap us_tj2
or enable it in /etc/X11/xorg.conf

You can configure KDE 4 to use the layout by changing LayoutList in the file
~/.kde/share/config/kxkbrc . On Gnome, you can edit the GConf value at
/desktop/gnome/peripherals/keyboard/kdb/layouts with gconf-editor.

On older systems that do not use evdev to configure the keyboard layout, you
can add the layout to the xkb listings on your machine. For the layout to
show up in the layout list presented by KDE, add the following line to the
layout section of /usr/share/X11/xkb/rules/xorg.lst:
    us_tj2          US/German (TJ, v2)

If you want it to appear in GNOME (and gdm, etc), add the following to the
<layoutList> section of /usr/share/X11/xkb/rules/xorg.xml:

    <layout>
      <configItem>
        <name>us_tj2</name>
        <description>US/German (TJ, v2)</description>
        <languageList><iso639Id>eng</iso639Id>
                      <iso639Id>ger</iso639Id>
                      <iso639Id>spa</iso639Id>
                      <iso639Id>por</iso639Id>
                      <iso639Id>epo</iso639Id>
                      <iso639Id>dan</iso639Id>
                      <iso639Id>nor</iso639Id>
                      <iso639Id>swe</iso639Id>
                      <iso639Id>dut</iso639Id>
                      <iso639Id>fra</iso639Id></languageList>
      </configItem>
      <variantList/>
    </layout>

